l lactogen increases insulin sensitivity","Human placental lactogen causes insulin resistance","Placental glucose transporters are downregulated","Maternal insulin production decreases","Fetal glucose requirements decrease as pregnancy progresses"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy is a naturally diabetogenic state characterised by progressive insulin resistance. \u003Cstrong\u003EHuman placental lactogen causes insulin resistance\u003C/strong\u003E to ensure adequate glucose supply to the fetus. This hormone, along with other pregnancy hormones like progesterone and placental growth hormone, reduces maternal insulin sensitivity by up to 60% by late pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman placental lactogen increases insulin sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E - This hormone decreases insulin sensitivity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental glucose transporters are downregulated\u003C/strong\u003E - These transporters are upregulated to facilitate increased glucose transfer to the fetus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal insulin production decreases\u003C/strong\u003E - The pancreas increases insulin production to compensate for insulin resistance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFetal glucose requirements decrease\u003C/strong\u003E - Fetal glucose demands increase significantly as pregnancy progresses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo maintain normal blood glucose levels, maternal pancreatic beta cells increase insulin production up to three times the non-pregnant state. If this compensation is inadequate, gestational diabetes may develop.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Human placental lactogen and other pregnancy hormones create insulin resistance during pregnancy","Placental 